         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Grafton Road ¶ Auckland ¶ 17' Jany 1872 ¶ My dear Baron von Mueller ¶  ¶ Three letters from you ¶  remind me forcibly of something like carelessness on my part in neglecting to reply I have however be...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">72.01.17</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Thomas Kirk</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M70, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Grafton Road</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Auckland</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">17' Jany 1872</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Baron von Mueller</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Three letters from you<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letters not found.</p>
               </note> remind me forcibly of something like carelessness on my part in neglecting to reply I have however been overworked and thoroughly ill therefrom, so that for a time <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">all work</hi>
               </seg>, especially writing was necessarily laid aside.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Rhabdothamnus%20Solandri">Rhabdothamnus Solandri</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>. I will endeavour to send a suite of specimens together with some other plants looked out for you. <name key="Dacrydium%20Kirkii">Dacrydium Kirkii</name>
               <name key="Isoete%20">Isoete </name>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>&amp;c &amp;c</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Hydrocotyle</hi>
               </seg> I think you already possess specn from the Great Barrier.:<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Great Barrier Island, Hauraki Gulf, east of Auckland, NZ.</p>
               </note> has not your H. <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">pterocarpa</hi>
               </seg> "winged" fruit? I will send specn of our plant.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Colensoa">Colensoa</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>, is only found in the extreme north, I have none in cultivation.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Arundinaria%20macrosperma">Arundinaria macrosperma</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>. — I can send you roots, but have no dried specn I will also forward roots of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Rhabdothamnus</hi>
               </seg> as soon as the dry season is past.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have never seen <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Rhabdothamnus</hi>
               </seg> more than 8 feet in height. When growing amongst shaded rocks it is usually laden with flowers and forms a striking object, but is obstinate enough under cultivation</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>When recovering I went to the Bay of Isds<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bay of Islands, NZ.</p>
               </note> for a week or two but was unable to get about to any extent. I saw <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Ackama">Ackama</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> in flower, noble trees 70 feet high — with flowers resembling <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Spirea</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Spiraea</seg>?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline"> barbata</hi>
               </seg> and foliage surpassing <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Pyrus</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">aucuparia</hi>
               </seg> wh it closely resembles My only other plant of note was <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Pittosporum</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">pimeleoides</hi>
               </seg> (wh I now have under cultn<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">cultivation.</p>
               </note>) it is united with P. <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">reflexum</hi>
               </seg> by my P. <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Gilliesianum</hi>
               </seg> wh is intermediate</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Next week I start for the hot lake country and hope to ascend Tongariro and Ruapahau <note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Ruapehu?</p>
               </note>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>wh rise to 8,000f<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">feet.</p>
               </note> in the centre of the island</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Believe me to be with kind regards</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. Kirk</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Can you determine the enclosed rayless Anthemide for me<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Pencilled addition by Kirk.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
